disease_name: Exposure to chemical explosion with undetermined intent
causes: Exposure to chemical mutagens in the environment
prevention: Early intervention and prevention through genetic screening
family_risk_increase: Family members can take appropriate preventive and monitoring measures to detect and treat potential health problems early
screening_recommendations: Genetic screening can detect an individual's risk of developing certain diseases before clinical symptoms appear
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic screening can help assess health risks and develop tailored health management plans

disease_name: Neoplasms of unknown behaviour of unspecified respiratory organ or intrathoracic organ
causes: genetic mutations; inherited conditions; exposure to radiation; carcinogenic substances; occupational hazards
risk_factors: family history of similar growths; exposure to chemicals; asbestos exposure
prognosis: Neoplasms of uncertain behaviour pose a unique challenge due to their unpredictable nature.
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic mutations or inherited conditions can increase the likelihood of developing neoplasms of uncertain behaviour.

disease_name: Traumatic amputation of right foot at ankle level
symptoms: phantom limb pain; dysesthesia at the level of the absent limb
causes: motor vehicle accidents; industrial accidents; combat injuries; crush injuries; severe burns
risk_factors: peripheral artery disease; hypertension; high thrombocyte levels; diabetes; smoking
prevention: safety measures in industrial settings; road safety education; management of chronic conditions
prognosis: The prognosis can vary significantly based on the severity of the injury and the patient's overall health, but recovery may involve ongoing pain management and rehabilitation.

symptoms: inability to return the foreskin to its normal position; swelling of the foreskin and tip of the penis; pain in the affected area; dark red or blue discoloration of the tip of the penis
causes: pulling back the foreskin for cleaning or stretching; medical procedures such as catheterization; incomplete circumcision; forcibly retracting the foreskin before it is ready
treatment_options: manual reduction by pressing on the head of the penis while pushing the foreskin forward; surgical intervention such as circumcision if manual reduction fails
risk_factors: being uncircumcised; age (more common in adolescents and older men); diabetes; history of bacterial infections
prevention: avoiding forcible retraction of the foreskin; proper hygiene practices
prognosis: The outcome is likely to be excellent if the condition is diagnosed and treated quickly.

disease_name: Multiple open wounds of thoracic wall
symptoms: breathing difficulties; chest pain; internal bleeding; shock
causes: penetrating injuries; blunt force trauma; accidents; assaults
treatment_options: surgical intervention; wound care; pain management; antibiotics
diagnosis_methods: physical examination; imaging studies (X-ray, CT scan); patient history
risk_factors: high-risk activities (e.g., sports, combat); lack of protective gear; previous chest injuries
prevention: use of seatbelts; wearing protective gear during high-risk activities; safety training
prognosis: The prognosis varies depending on the severity of the wounds and associated injuries; timely medical intervention is crucial.

symptoms: Rapid breathing rate (over 60 breaths per minute); Grunting sounds with breathing; Flaring of the nostrils; Retractions (pulling in at the ribs with breathing)
causes: Delayed postpartum resorption of fetal lung fluid; Cesarean section without labor; Maternal conditions such as diabetes and asthma
treatment_options: Oxygen therapy; Antibiotics; Diuretics; Intravenous fluids for nutrition if feeding is withheld
diagnosis_methods: Monitoring the baby for 2 to 3 days; Exclusion of other respiratory conditions
risk_factors: Cesarean delivery; Maternal diabetes; Maternal asthma
prognosis: Transient tachypnea of the newborn is a benign, self-limited condition that usually resolves within 3 days.

symptoms: sore throat; difficulty swallowing; pain during swallowing; redness in the throat
causes: viral infections; bacterial infections; irritants and toxins; allergic reactions
treatment_options: antibiotics for bacterial infections; corticosteroids for symptom relief; gargles; acetaminophen or NSAIDs for pain relief
diagnosis_methods: physical examination; throat swab for bacterial testing; history of symptoms
risk_factors: exposure to irritants; allergies; weakened immune system; recent infections
prevention: avoiding irritants; good hygiene practices; staying hydrated; avoiding close contact with infected individuals
prognosis: Most cases resolve without complications, but persistent symptoms may require further evaluation.

disease_name: Fracture avulsion or collateral ligament rupture of medial malleolus with fracture of fibula above syndesmosis and fracture of posterior margin of distal tibia
symptoms: pain in the ankle; swelling around the ankle; bruising; difficulty bearing weight
causes: trauma or injury to the ankle; twisting motion of the ankle
treatment_options: surgical fixation for unstable fractures; nonsurgical treatment for stable fractures
diagnosis_methods: physical examination; X-rays; MRI for soft tissue evaluation
risk_factors: high-impact sports; falls; previous ankle injuries
prevention: strengthening exercises for ankle stability; proper footwear; avoiding high-risk activities
prognosis: With appropriate treatment, most patients can expect a good recovery, although some may develop arthritis if not treated properly.

symptoms: neck pain; headache; Horner's syndrome; cranial-nerve palsy; neurological symptoms; autonomic symptoms
causes: Ehlers-Danlos syndrome (EDS); traumatic injuries; degenerative diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis
diagnosis_methods: clinical evaluation; upright MRI; digital motion X-ray; flexion-extension scans
risk_factors: genetic disorders; trauma to the neck; prior history of neck and musculoskeletal pain; jobs that require a lot of desk work; low social support; job insecurity; physical weakness; poor computer station setup
prognosis: The prognosis for patients varies significantly based on the severity of the instability, underlying cause, and treatment success. Some may require surgery, and residual symptoms from coexisting conditions can persist.
inheritance_pattern: autosomal dominant inheritance and autosomal recessive inheritance
family_risk_increase: family history of connective tissue disorders may increase risk
genetic_risk_assessment: The most common genetic cause of cranio-cervical dissociation is Ehlers-Danlos syndrome, particularly the hypermobile type.

disease_name: Other specified malignant neoplasms of kidney except renal pelvis
symptoms: Blood in urine; Flank pain; Loss of appetite; Unexplained weight loss; Persistent tiredness; Fever; Night sweats
causes: Exact causes are unknown; Inherited genetic changes in certain genes
diagnosis_methods: Medical history evaluation; Imaging tests (e.g., CT scan, MRI)
risk_factors: Excess body weight; High blood pressure; Family history of kidney cancer; Smoking; Long-term dialysis
prevention: Quit smoking; Maintain a healthy weight; Manage blood pressure
prognosis: Prognosis varies based on stage at diagnosis and treatment response.
inheritance_pattern: Hereditary cancer syndromes account for 5%-8% of kidney cancers.
family_risk_increase: Higher risk for individuals with a strong family history of kidney cancer.
hereditary_factors: Inherited cancer syndromes; Pathogenic variants in certain genes
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic counseling may be recommended for individuals with a family history of kidney cancer.

symptoms: bilious vomiting; distended abdomen; absence of meconium within 24 to 48 hours
causes: jejunoileal atresia; paralytic ileus; mechanical obstruction due to fibrous bands, hernias, or tumors
diagnosis_methods: clinical examination; imaging studies (e.g., X-rays, ultrasound)
prevention: treating underlying conditions that may lead to obstruction; Not specified
prognosis: With advancements in surgical techniques and care, the overall survival rate has improved significantly.

disease_name: Puncture wound with foreign body of shoulder or upper arm
symptoms: pain; swelling; redness; difficulty moving the affected area
causes: sharp and pointed objects (e.g., nails); bites; stepping on rusty metal
treatment_options: cleaning the wound; applying antibiotic cream; applying a bandage; stitches or staples for deeper cuts; antibiotics to prevent infection
diagnosis_methods: physical examination; ICD-10 coding for classification
risk_factors: deep puncture wounds; foreign body presence
prevention: prompt medical attention for deep puncture wounds; proper wound cleaning
prognosis: Puncture wounds can become infected if not treated properly, but with appropriate care, healing is generally favorable.

symptoms: muscle weakness; fatigue; cramping; palpitations; constipation; nausea; vomiting; excessive urination; excessive thirst
causes: excessive loss of potassium due to vomiting; diarrhea; laxative use; inadequate potassium intake; prolonged diuretic use; hyperhidrosis; hypomagnesemia; genetic conditions
treatment_options: potassium supplementation; treatment of underlying conditions
diagnosis_methods: serum potassium level measurement; clinical evaluation
prevention: adequate potassium intake during pregnancy; monitoring of potassium levels in at-risk newborns
prognosis: With adequate control of potassium levels and resolution of any predisposing condition, the prognosis is excellent.
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic assessment may be relevant in cases of hereditary hypokalemia, but specific assessments are not detailed.

symptoms: erythema; swelling; blisters; exudation; peeling; burning; itching; hyperpigmentation
causes: exposure to photosensitizing drugs; exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation
treatment_options: avoidance of the causative agent; photoprotection; symptomatic relief measures; use of broad-spectrum sunscreens; taking photoprotective medications
diagnosis_methods: history of skin problem arising from sunlight exposure; skin examination; specific tests including photosets
risk_factors: older age; use of certain medications (e.g., NSAIDs, antimicrobials, antidepressants)
prevention: use sun protection; avoid contact with known allergens; stay indoors during peak sunlight hours; fully cover the skin
prognosis: In most patients, the prognosis is excellent once the offending agent is removed, though complete resolution may take weeks to months for some compounds.

symptoms: fatigue; lack of pleasure; anxiety; irritability; sleepiness; agitation; extreme suspicion; paranoia; depression; powerful cravings for cocaine
causes: cessation of cocaine use; binge ending
risk_factors: chronic, regular use of cocaine; previous substance use disorders
prognosis: Cocaine addiction is difficult to treat, and relapse can occur. Symptoms may last for months, and treatment should start with the least restrictive option.
hereditary_factors: genetic predisposition to addiction; family history of substance use disorders

symptoms: compulsive skin picking; significant skin damage; feelings of guilt, shame, and embarrassment; social withdrawal; self-injury
causes: genetic predisposition; underlying mental health conditions (e.g., OCD, ADHD, ASD); individual temperament; stress
treatment_options: medication; therapy; identifying triggers; addressing underlying conditions
diagnosis_methods: clinical assessment based on DSM-5 criteria
risk_factors: family history of excoriation disorder or other body-focused repetitive behaviors; higher-than-average rates of mood and anxiety disorders in first-degree relatives
prognosis: Excoriation disorder can be chronic and may last from 5 to 21 years if untreated, with potential for remission.
hereditary_factors: genetic predisposition to body-focused repetitive behaviors
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic factors may contribute to the likelihood of developing excoriation disorder, particularly in individuals with a family history.

symptoms: rhinitis; nonproductive cough; sore throat; headache; fever; chills; malaise; shortness of breath; earache; muscle aches; vomiting; nausea; diarrhea
risk_factors: older age; pre-existing lung disease; diabetes; cardiovascular comorbidities
prevention: annual influenza vaccination; good hygiene practices
prognosis: Influenza can lead to significant morbidity and mortality, especially in vulnerable populations such as children and seniors.

symptoms: nausea; vomiting; dizziness; light-headedness; irritability; headache; thirst; weakness; excessive sweating; muscle cramps; decreased urine output
causes: high environmental temperatures; intense physical exertion; chronic medical conditions; history of heat illness; febrile illness
diagnosis_methods: physical examination; review of symptoms; vital signs assessment
risk_factors: chronic medical conditions; history of heat illness; high environmental temperatures; intense physical exertion
prevention: staying hydrated; avoiding strenuous activity in high temperatures
prognosis: Generally good with prompt treatment and prevention measures.
family_risk_increase: Higher risk if family members have a history of heat-related illnesses.
genetic_risk_assessment: Genetic testing may identify susceptibility to heat-related illnesses, particularly in individuals with a family history.
